Despite the variety of clinical data available which enabled the model personalisation presented in “Data Processing Pipeline” and “Personalised Cardiac Mechanics Model” sections, certain modelling aspects could not be determined and needed to be based on literature studies. With the objective of achieving reliable parametrisation through improving model accuracy, model assumptions regarding fibre distribution, suitable boundary conditions and the reference state were carefully analysed. The pipeline was applied with perturbations of these assumptions on all volunteer and patient cases, to enable a systematic assessment of model uncertainties. Model accuracy and parameter identifiability were then examined through characterisation of the objective function \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
